<taxonomicNameLabel box="[476,557,1944,1968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 6. Frontal view of head. 7. Anterolateral view of head. 8. Clypeus. 9. Dorsal view of head. 10. Antenna 11. Closeup of antenna with coeloconica sensillae. 12. Wings.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876439" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6876439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876439/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" startId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" targetBox="[168,1420,181,1920]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1943,2004]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,342,1943,1967]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">FIGURES 13–18.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Zhang &amp; Sasan &amp; O’Kennon &amp; Kranz, 2022" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Sasan &amp; O’Kennon &amp; Kranz" authorityYear="2022" box="[349,483,1944,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[349,483,1944,1968]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Druon laceyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[491,573,1944,1968]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[491,573,1944,1968]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 13. Lateral view of mesosoma. 14. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 15. Tarsal claw. 16. Propodeum. 17. Lateral view of metasoma. 18. Ovipositor tip.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">
Metasoma longer than head + mesosoma, higher than long in lateral view; T2 very short (not reach ⅓ of the metasomal length), all tergites smooth; T2 with setae on the anterior half, T7 and hypopygium setose (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1423,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[168,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Druon laceyi sp. nov.. 13. Lateral view of mesosoma. 14. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 15. Tarsal claw. 16. Propodeum. 17. Lateral view of metasoma. 18. Ovipositor tip." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876439/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). Ventral spine of hypopygium slender, prominent part at least 2.4× as long as broad, with sparse, long white setae, extending beyond the apex of spine (
<figureCitation box="[564,647,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[168,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Druon laceyi sp. nov.. 13. Lateral view of mesosoma. 14. Dorsal view of mesosoma. 15. Tarsal claw. 16. Propodeum. 17. Lateral view of metasoma. 18. Ovipositor tip." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876439/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">
Gall. Small clusters of 1-10 individual (unilocular) brown oval cells in the center of the leaf, emerging perpendicular from the midrib on both upper and lower leaf sides of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang &amp; Sasan &amp; O’Kennon &amp; Kranz" authorityYear="2022" box="[857,959,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceyi">
<emphasis box="[857,959,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Q. laceyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the fall (
<figureCitation box="[1093,1203,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Druon laceyi sp. nov.. 1. Quercus laceyi with mature galls. 2. Mature galls with an emergence hole. 3. Cross section of gall showing adult and empty chambers. 4. Live anterodorsal habitus. 5. Lateral habitus of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876433" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876433/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Figs. 1–2</figureCitation>
). Seen in abundance on nearly every leaf of each affected host. The cell surface when examined with a microscope shows numerous minute papillae covered with a crystalline material and sparse long white woolly hairs. The hairs weather away as the galls age, except near the base. Inside is a single thin-walled chamber (
<figureCitation box="[988,1057,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Druon laceyi sp. nov.. 1. Quercus laceyi with mature galls. 2. Mature galls with an emergence hole. 3. Cross section of gall showing adult and empty chambers. 4. Live anterodorsal habitus. 5. Lateral habitus of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876433" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876433/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Cells stay firmly attached to the leaf when it falls. Leaf petioles frequently display a small darkened area, presumably where eggs were inserted. Approximately 
<quantity box="[293,379,511,537]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[490,569,510,537]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5mm</quantity>
in diameter. Seen in Fort Worth, TX in October. Adults emerge the following February (
<figureCitation box="[268,337,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[182,1405,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Druon laceyi sp. nov.. 1. Quercus laceyi with mature galls. 2. Mature galls with an emergence hole. 3. Cross section of gall showing adult and empty chambers. 4. Live anterodorsal habitus. 5. Lateral habitus of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876433" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876433/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="69" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,582,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Biology.</emphasis>
Only the asexual generation of this species is known, inducing aggregated detachable leaf galls on the top and bottom of the midrib of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang &amp; Sasan &amp; O’Kennon &amp; Kranz" authorityYear="2022" box="[520,622,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceyi">
<emphasis box="[520,622,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Q. laceyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition to the gall inducer, inquilines (
<taxonomicName box="[1115,1236,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cynipidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Hartig, 1840" authorityName="Hartig" authorityYear="1840" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Synergus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1350,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Synergus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hartig, T." pageId="6" pageNumber="69" pagination="176 - 209" refId="ref5601" refString="Hartig, T. (1840) Uber die Familie der Gallwespen. Zeitschrift fur Entomologie, 2, 176 - 209. [in German]" type="journal article" year="1840">Hartig, 1840</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) and parasitoids (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1833" box="[410,550,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Eupelmidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Eupelmidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Cameron, 1884" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1884" box="[561,842,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Eupelmidae" genus="Brasema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[561,661,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Brasema</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cameron, P." box="[669,842,655,681]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 124" refId="ref5276" refString="Cameron, P. (1884) Fam. Chalcididae [continued]. In: Godman, F. D., Salvin, D. (Ed.), Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Hymenoptera. (Families Tenthredinidae-Chrysididae.). Taylor and Francis, London, pp. 1 - 124." type="book chapter" year="1884">Cameron, 1884</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
&amp; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1856" box="[880,1006,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Ormyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ormyridae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[1017,1314,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Ormyridae" genus="Ormyrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1017,1117,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="69">Ormyrus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Westwood, J. O." box="[1124,1314,655,681]" pageId="6" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 127" refId="ref6893" refString="Westwood, J. O. (1832) Descriptions of several new British forms amongst the parasitic hymenopterous insects. Philosophical Magazine, 3, 1 - 127. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14786443208647849" type="journal article" year="1832">Westwood, 1832</bibRefCitation>
